Data Science Pipeline Tutorial:
What Are the World's Rising National Film Industries?

One of the classes I took this semester was FILM298D: Film Art in a Global Society. The course was, as you might guess, about cinema around the globe, giving a broad view of modern film industries across many countries. I got to see a lot of good movies, but I was saddened to see that most of them were not well known outside of film festivals and critical circles, as most countries' everyday movie theaters and streaming options are dominated by American and other Anglophone films. However, I also heard that the national film industries of many non-Anglophone countries are growing, and this inspired me to look at the data of global film production to determine just which countries' film industries are rising and how. In this tutorial I will seek to determine which countries' film industries are expanding the fastest, in terms of total pictures produced annually, pictures produced intranationally, and pictures produced via international coproductions.

Tim Hicks

The table I want to use is "Culture/Feature Films/Feature Films (full dataset)". I have downloaded the table and have reuploaded it to GitHub for use here. This data set covers the film production of most countries in the world from 2011 to 2017.

Managing the Data

At over 30,000 rows of information, we suddenly have a lot of data! This single UNESCO table contains 76 different categoriesindicated by the "Indicator" columnof information on feature film production, distribution of feature films, cinema infrastructure, and exhibition of feature films, and while all of it is interesting, most of it is extraneous for our purposes here. So, to make this data set more managable, I will extract three smaller tables containing the information we want. We can discard the rest.

What is the information we want? In this analysis we are looking at three main figures:

  • Total number of feature films produced by each country each year
  • Number of feature films that are produced 100% intranationally by each country each year
  • Number of feature films that are produced as international coproductions by each country each year
To be "produced by" a given country, at least one of a film's producers must be of that country. The film does not have to be shot, edited, or anything else in that country, merely funded there. This means that films that are international coproductions have multiple producers of multiple national origins.

First, the total number of feature films produced by each country each year. This value will be equal to the sum of the intranational productions and the coproductions of each country each year, so we shouldn't have to extract this table at all if we didn't want to, since we can just derive the value ourselves from our other data. But there are some countries and years for which this is the only data we have, with no additional breakdowns into domestic vs. international productions, so we need to take this table by itself as well if we want to have maximum access to the data.

Tidying the Data

Now that we have just the data we want, we can begin working with it, right? If you want to, sure. But the data is still a bit obtuse, so I want to refine it a bit further. At the moment, each of our three tables has multiple rows for each year and multiple rows for each country, which makes it a bit difficult to process or even look at the data without some unnecessary stress. So to resolve that, I am pivoting each of the tables so that there is one row for each year and one column for each country. Then I am dropping the "Value" super-header, since it adds no new information. This way it will be easy to look up the number of films of any type produced by any country in any year without having to use any more code than we have to.

In [8]:
natfilms = natfilms.pivot(index='Time', columns='Country')
natfilms.columns = natfilms.columns.droplevel()
In [9]:
intrafilms = intrafilms.pivot(index='Time', columns='Country')
intrafilms.columns = intrafilms.columns.droplevel()
In [10]:
cofilms = cofilms.pivot(index='Time', columns='Country')
cofilms.columns = cofilms.columns.droplevel()

Data Analysis

Labelling the country names corresponding to the lines on the graphs is a bit of a double edged-sword, as it is much better than having no labels at all, but most of the labels we do get overlap horribly to the point of unreadability. But these are just preliminary visualizations and will not be our most important graphs, so for our purposes it's okay if we can only read the labels for the top countries in each category. The alternative would be to make the text on each of these graphs unreasonably small, and I won't subject you to that.

Referring back to the data in the first tables, the one about total films produced each year, let's take a closer look. India is soaring far above everyone else, rising from about 1250 to 2000. Below India is a series of runners-up for the title of most feature films per year: China, the United States, and Japan, plus one really good year each for Nigeria and South Korea. Below these is a gap before everyone else is clustered at the bottom, spread from 0 to about 350.
India's numbers are rapidly rising, China's and Japan's are slowly rising, and the US's are slowly falling. It is nearly impossible to make a gut estimate about the growth rates of the rest of the countries at this point. To do that, we need to calculate a line of best fit for each nation's film production numbers and determine which has the highest slope. We will do that in the next step, but first, let's also examine the other two graphs.

Looking at the intranationally-produced films graph, India is again the major outlier. There is only data for India in this category in two years, 2014 and 2015, but we can see that in those years pretty all of India's massive number of films that we have data for were produced 100% in India. Over a thousand intranational films behind India is the United States, for which the vast majority of its films are intranationally-produced, although the coproduction graph shows that the US still coproduces more of its films than any other country, with the occasional exception of France. All other countries for which we have data produce no more than about 250 intranational films per year and up to a hundred coproductions per year, though most make far fewer.

Once we calculate which countries' film industries are growing the fastest, we can use this data to determine whether this rising success is due primarily to a focus on intranational productions, international coproductions, or a relatively even mix of both. So far it seems like India's insane film industry is probably growing the fastest in addition to being the biggest, but it is unclear what countries will be the runners-up. To determine thatas well as whether India truly is the current king of cinematic growthwe will need to use hypothesis testing and machine learning.

Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning

We want to know how fast each country's film production system has grown or shrunk over the course of our seven-year period, so for each country we use scikit-learn's linear model to use hypothesis testing and machine learning to estimate a line of best fit for each country's film production numbers over time. But before we do this, we first create a new dataframe that will serve as a nicer hash table to store the 7-year growth coefficient corresponding to each country.

In [68]:
filmgrowth = pd.DataFrame(np.array([[np.NaN] * len(natfilms.columns.values)]),
                          columns=natfilms.columns.values)
filmgrowth = filmgrowth.rename(index={0: 'Growth Coefficient'})

Here's where scikit-learn comes in. For each country, we create an independent variable list and a dependent variable list, and fill them in with the total annual film production data for each year where it is available. Then we have scikit-learn create a linear regression to estimate its line of best fit for the country's cinematic growth, and we store the growth coefficient for that country in our new dataframe.

In [72]:
# for each country
for c in natfilms.columns.values:
    # create empty lists for the data for the independent variable (years) and the dependent
    # variable (annual production numbers)
    ind = []
    dep = []
    # for each year in question, add it and its film count for the given country to the lists
    # if the data exists
    for y in natfilms.index.values:
        val = natfilms.at[y,c]
        if not(pd.isnull(val)):
            ind.append([y])
            dep.append(val)
    # create a linear regression to estimate a line of best fit, then store the coefficient of
    # that regression line; this is the national 7-year growth rate
    lm = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    lm.fit(ind, dep)
    filmgrowth.at['Growth Coefficient', c] = lm.coef_[0]

Nice. We also want to know which are the absolute fastest-expanding national film industries out of all of these, so we also make a copy of this dataframe that contains only the growth rates of the top ten countries. To do that I am dropping all columns for the copy for which the growth coefficient is below a certain threshhold. If you wanted you could write a function to figure out what that threshhold should be, but I just guessed values until I found the one I wanted: 10.5. This gives us our top ten rising national film industries: those of India, South Korea, China, the United Arab Emirates, Myanmar/Burma, Japan, Argentina, Turkey, Mexico, and Brazil. And yes, this means India absolutely is the king of national cinematic growth, wildly outpacing everybody else.

New Data Representation

Now that we have the growth rates for every country in our data set, as well as a list of the ten leaders, let's make some new, more interesting visuals to represent these finds. First, I want to be able to look at a world map and see which national film industries are expanding and which are consolidating or shrinking.

To do that, I am first creating a new dataframe that contains the coordinates of the geographic center of each country, at which points we will place markers indicating the growth rate of that country's film industry. I am getting the list of coordinates from https://worldmap.harvard.edu/data/geonode:country_centroids_az8.

Okay, now we can plot our points on a map. For each country for which we have a growth rate, we mark it at the corresponding latitude and longitude in our center points table, and we color each marker according to its growth rate. We also set them so that if one clicks on any of the markers, a popup will appear displaying that country's exact 7-year growth rate.

        lat = lat[0]
        lon = lon[0]
    # determine the color of the marker based on the national growth rate
    col = 'purple'
    rate = filmgrowth.at['Growth Coefficient',c]
    if rate <= -10:
         col = 'red'
    elif rate <= 0:
        col = 'orange'
    elif rate <= 10:
        col = 'lightblue'
    elif rate <= 20:
        col = 'lightgreen'
    elif rate <= 30:
        col = 'green'
    elif rate <= 50:
        col = 'darkgreen'
    # Set the popup to display the national growth rate
    info = '7-Year Average Growth Rate:\n' + str(filmgrowth.at['Growth Coefficient',c])
    # Plot the given country's marker on the map
    folium.Marker([lat, lon],popup=info,tooltip=c,icon=folium.Icon(color=col,icon='film')).add_to(wmap)
wmap

Markers are colored according to the following criteria:

  • Red: National film production is decreasing, with a coefficient of -10 or less per year
  • Orange: National film production is decreasing or static, with a coefficient of -90 per year
  • Light blue: National film production is increasing, with a coefficient of 110 per year
  • Light green: National film production is increasing, with a coefficient of 1120 per year
  • Medium green: National film production is increasing, with a coefficient of 2130 per year
  • Dark green: National film production is increasing, with a coefficient of 3150 per year
  • Purple: National film production is increasing, with a coefficient of 50 or more per year!

Further Data Analysis

Alright! That's a lot of graphs, so let's start to examine them. In the map we can see what parts of the world are investing in more or fewer films than they used to. More films are being made each year in many parts of Europe, Latin America, and southeast Asia, and the biggest increases in production are happening in eastern and southern Asia, particularly in Japan, Myanmar/Burma, the United Arab Emirates, China, South Korea, and, of course, India, the country which far and away takes the cake for the title of largest cinematic growth rate. Film production is down in central and western Africa, as well as in many Western countries that tend to loom large in the international film trade, including the United Kingdom, New Zealand, and especially the United States, with the USA suffering from the largest average decrease in film production numbers of any country for which we have data. The data doesn't offer any explanations for these global trends, so we will have to make our own inferences, which I will do in the conclusion.

Next, the charts showing the absolute numbers of intranational and international feature films produced by the top ten fastest-growing national film industries. Of the top ten, China and India are both the two fastest-growing and the largest producers of films in terms of sheer number. However, the UAE manages to be the third-fastest expanding national film industry, despite producing the smallest number of feature films per year of any in the top ten. This is especially impressive given that this rise in production only began to rise from almost nothing in 2014, halfway through the epoch we are examining. South Korea also only began to seriously increase its film production numbers around 2014, despite us having data for that nation covering the entire period in question.
And as for the production of intranational films versus coproductions, we can see that, of the countries in the top ten for which we have more specific data, all produce many more films of the former type than than of the latter, though as production of the former has risen, so too has production of the latter. Furthermore, some countries, particularly Argentina, have been focusing especially on coproductions, as their number of coproductions has been rising faster than their number of intranational productions.

Finally, how do the top ten rising national film industries's ratios of intranational to international films compare to each other and to the rest of the world? The last of our charts illustrates this. This chart is a bit unpleasant to read, with small font and overlapping labels again, but again I didn't want to make the graph so big that it became impossible to read anyway. As we can see, the vast majority of countries produce very small numbers of films at all, and the ones they do produce tend to be coproductions. Of the countries that do produce a substantial number of intranational films, they still make a sizable number of coproductions. France is unique among these countries in that it has the closest ratio of intranational films to coproductions. Among our top ten, Argentina leads in both intranational and international productions. Mexico also puts a sizeable emphasis on coproductions, approaching Argentina in number, which gives it notable standing above Brazil and Turkey, which make similar numbers of intranational films to Mexico each year, but engage in far fewer coproductions.

Conclusion

I am excited to see countries that are not the traditional leaders in world cinema stepping up their film production. I hope that movies from these places continue to become more available to the rest of the world, so that we all have increased opportunity to leave our usual cultural points of view and broaden our understanding of reality. I do wonder what is motivating these changes in production numbers in these particular countries, and while the data doesn't say, I can hypothesize.

In authoritarian countries like China and the UAE, I think a lot of the increases in production are motivated by government action as part of efforts to modernize, grow the national economies, and decrease reliance of domestic audiences on imported films for entertainment. Movies from these nations are very valuable and worthy of interest; I have seen enough Soviet films to know that artists always try to find a way to communicate their most important ideas, even in the face of government censorship.
Entertainment from countries like Mexico, Brazil, Japan, and South Korea (countries either in or with strong ties to the West) is becoming increasingly in demand thanks to modern media's popularization of many national genres and auteurs (Bong Joon-Ho, Alejandro Gonzlez Irritu, Kleber Mendona Filho, Hayao Miyazaki, etc.) for international audiences.
As for the shrinking number of films per year in the US, I don't think this means the American film industry is diminishing. Rather, American producers are increasingly spending larger amounts of money on fewer and fewer films each year, with funds that used to go towards more diverse projects now being pooled for the budgets of a few "safe bet" films that are usually about a pre-existing franchise that is already familiar with general audiences.
While American movie producers are making larger bets on a relatively small number of films by well-known filmmakers working with well-known properties (generally aiming for "safe bet" films), it excites me that some countries are becoming more adventurous and growing their film industries through increased production and increased diversity of production. To make this happen, many of these nations are investing in more international coproductions, presumably in order to reach a wider audience and to shoulder less of the financial burden of making a film. Cinematic coproductions can be really cool (if you haven't watched Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon, do it now), and their benefits are really helpful for artists in many countries that have less of a voice on the international cultural stage, but intranational films are also incredibly important and useful in communicating ideas unique to a certain culture and context. So I hope to see those rise as well.

Finally, this data is, of course, all from the pre-COVID beforetimes. So the pandemic may have shifted the course of the trends that we observe here. Film production in 2020 was obviously way down, which has all sorts of ramifications in the film industry, just on its own, to say nothing of the massive loss of life in many of the countries we have looked at here. But I don't think that ultimately the pandemic will completely derail these trends. Hinder them, yes, but I think that, like the film industries we have looked at here, they will eventually resume their rise.
